segments.text: November 19 testing the mics to see if they are working November 19 testing the mics to see if they are working November 19
Testing a second time November twenty second Albuquerque in New Mexico.
Weather is getting cooler outside and have the pleasure of chatting with a fellow graduate of high school in orange Mike Godwin try your mic test testing this is Mike Godwin.
Mike why did you attend A&M instead of some other school what led you to make that choice.

Well, although my father was not an Aggie, in fact my father only took a couple of courses at Lamar University in Beaumont, he had been a lifelong Aggie fan and we attended a lot of football games as I was growing up going to College Station and I would say it was really the football game and the traditions and the band and all of those things that
They convinced me and we were fortunate enough to see the famous football game probably in 1965 that had the Texas special sitting in the end zone when they pulled that trick off.
And that sort of cinched it for me that that's where I wanted to go.
That quarterback had been in my freshman history 105 class.
When you came as a freshman, how did you get there?
How did you arrive and what did you bring with you?
Well, I came in, you know, all full of expectations and cockiness, I think a lot of us did.
And my first memories were when the parents were standing around, how nice the upperclassmen were.
But as soon as the parents were out of shouting range, it changed very quickly.
And I would say the first 24 hours at A&M was a real adjustment.
You came, your parents brought you in the car?
Brought me in the car.
And you didn't have a car?
Didn't have a car, no.
Never had a car until my senior year.
What gear, what stuff did you bring?
I don't even remember.
It wasn't much though.
I mean you weren't allowed that many things.
I don't remember anything.
And you were in the Corps?
In the Corps, in F-1.
Why that unit?
I started out in engineering and that was an engineering outfit and arrived on campus actually that year.
We arrived on campus before school started because the first football game that year was actually, as I recall, a couple days before classes actually began.
So they took a bunch of high school kids that didn't know anything about the Corps or military and all of a sudden we were marching and trying to get ready for that first football game.
And describe your room and your roommate, your official lady.
My official lady actually was a fellow named Edward Hickey who came with us.
There were, I actually went to a very small Catholic high school in Orange, Texas.
There were I think 36 graduates out of that class and four of us went to A&M.
And I'd like to think that the other three came because I encouraged them to go.
Edward Hickey was one of them, and he and I were fish roommates that first year.
Where, what dorm and so forth?
I don't even remember.
I believe it was, the whole time I was there, we were even in the, I don't even remember the actual names, dorm two and dorm four.
Okay.
In fact, the core headquarters, I believe, was in two.
And I think that's where we first started out my fish year.
And what was the nickname for your outfit?
Did it have a nickname?
The Finest First, which is not even there anymore.
And then my fish year, we won, I think probably my first two years, we were the General Moore outfit for Best All-Around Outfits.
make believe that I had known nothing about what it was like to be a freshman at Texas A&M describe your fish year.
It was not always a lot of fun.
First of all, the whole thing.
It's amazing when equalizer when two things happen when you get your head shaved, and everybody's dressed to life.
And I think it was a very good experience.
although it was a sobering experience.
Having grown up as an only child, I wasn't used to having a lot of people telling me what to do, also.
And very quickly, having upperclassmen yelling at you and whatever, it really, it did, again, as I recall,

high school, coming from a small high school, and in high school I was involved in everything, the student government, and in a sense were sort of a big man on campus, and all of a sudden you're this insignificant little nothing at A&M, along with all of your fellow members of your fish class.
So I think that had a lot to do with it.
I think I was not used to the yelling and screaming and the running in the middle of the night and the other stuff.
And I think after about the first semester of my fish year, it got a little bit better, but not a lot.
I can remember having many phone calls home and my parents coming in on the weekend because I just needed it to happen.
But it was certainly a bonding experience with fellow members of the fish class.
What about hazing?
What events were there that today would be classified as hazing?

Well, I think that stealing the CO's footlocker, which was a big tradition back then, and presenting it on Thanksgiving Day, there was a lot of hazing that went on to try to uncover where that footlocker

did did y'all were you a party to that theft uh yes i was and where did y'all where how'd you get it and where'd you put it um you know what i don't even remember how we got it or where we all i i can't remember the fun parts all i can remember was sweating in the middle of the night and three o'clock in the morning doing um push-ups and stuff in the showers and everything else is the ceo acting very upset that we had taken his his um footlocker but
probably secretly hoping that no one would crack so that his would be presented on the field on Thanksgiving Day.
About how long in advance of that game was it?
As I recall, it was about two weeks of hell.
Two long weeks.
And how many of you were involved in the theft?
I think just about the whole fish class was involved.
We all certainly paid the penalty for it.
And I think the CO was involved.
Secretly glad when at the end no one cracked me.
What were some of the punishments?
You said push-ups in the wee hours of the morning.
Push-ups running first thing in the morning.
It was one of the few times that all of a sudden the academic side of you, you're saying, we shouldn't be doing this because it's hurting our schoolwork.
But had it not been the punishment that we were receiving, it probably wouldn't have been quite so concerning.
How often was the board used?
You know what, actually, by the time I was there, we didn't really have that.
I can honestly say that the old grab poops and that part of it, there was very little of that.
I think it was more just straight physical torture.
Did you fish retaliate ever with some drown outs?
A few, yes.
Who were the favorite targets?
Well, I think some of our sophomore leaders were the subject of those quite frequently.
Then there was always the story that I don't know that it was a it ever happened, but it was certainly making the rounds when we were there.
The upperclassmen who quite a few people didn't like that lived on

the third or fourth floor of one of the dorms that supposedly they snuck in and recreated his room on the first floor secretly as he was sleeping and without waking him up put him on the first floor and then came in and made a mad show of getting ready to throw him out the window thinking that he was being thrown out of the third or fourth floor when in fact he was only in the first floor and they tossed him out the window i don't know if that was true or not but that was
When I was there, that was a story that was going around that had happened.
That it happened that year?
Sometime in that time.
Oh, really?
Oh, that's good.
That's a good Aggie story.
Describe chow hall, a typical chow hall meal for a fish, your freshman year.
You didn't get a lot to eat by the time you got through going through all the requests of the upperclassmen.
as a fish, I don't recall eating very much at all.
I can remember sneaking out on campus or spending a lot of times at the MSC eating because we didn't have a chance to eat a lot.
In fact, I can remember my parents saying, how come you're spending so much money on food when your room and board is included in what we're paying?
But I will say that by the time I got to be a sophomore, I put on about 20 pounds.
I can remember chicken fried steak and lots of milk and
make enough for not eating as a fish.
What were your favorite Aggie foods, dining hall foods?
Probably chicken fried steak.
Lots of beef.
Was there a nickname for chicken fried steak?
I've not heard one.
I don't think so.
I don't recall.
What was your least favorite?
I don't recall I even had a least favorite.
We had lots of beef though.
What about desserts?
Must have been some that you enjoyed.
I don't remember.
Let's see.
Nicknames for beverages that were on the table.
Tea.
I don't know.
Did anybody ever have lemonade?
Did coffee have a nickname?
I don't know.
I think it was mostly just water, iced tea, and milk.
Mostly milk.
Describe beginning with whenever you got up.
Run me through a typical day of classes, a Monday through Friday.
What time did you get up and what did you do as a freshman?
It seems like Reveille probably was around 6 o'clock.
And I think we probably fell out about 6.30, 6.45 to march to breakfast.
at Duncan.
And then I think we were probably back at the dorm about 730.
I remember shining a lot of shoes, using a lot of Brasso, getting everything ready.
Then typically would, you know, go to morning classes.
I think that probably there were a lot of lunches that I passed on just so I could avoid the midday hazing at the lunch table.
I can remember taking lots and lots and lots of naps.
It seems like we were back in my hole.
And I think that probably the less visible you were in many cases, the better.
It's probably good just to sort of slink in and slink out and not get hasty.
Then afternoons, what happened?
Afternoons actually, as I recall, was not bad.
I mean, I know that there was
remember intramurals.
And I can't remember how much intramurals happened as a fish and how much it was after that.
But I remember that being actually an enjoyable part of the day.
We did that and then usually seemed like we would get together then late in the afternoon and we'd march or do military type drills and stuff until we went in for the evening.
And then
you know, March to evening chow, and would come back, and they were pretty serious.
Our outfit, again, because it was a General Moore outfit, was pretty serious about the grades, and being an engineering outfit, they took the academic side of it pretty seriously.
And I can remember coming back, and we'd have study hall, and spending a good amount of time studying every night.
All right, in terms of going to class, for you and your classmates, how often did y'all cut class as freshmen and sophomores?
I would say a fair amount my freshman year, my sophomore year.
For me personally, it was a lot.
When you cut class, where'd you go?
MSC?
Oh, we'd go to the MSC, drink a lot of coffee.
I can remember taking some afternoon drives, and I can't even remember quite where it was, but it was the place that you could drive to that you could actually buy liquor.
And, you know, going and having a few beers in the afternoon.
Nothing a lot, but just going out for a nice drive and, you know, picking up some beer and coming back.
I remember that a lot.
And having come from a high school
that grades came pretty easily to me.
And I thought that things were going to come pretty easily to me my first two years.
And frankly, was probably not prepared as well as I should have and wasn't as serious about academics as I should have.
So consequently, yes, we cut a lot of classes my sophomore year.
My roommate then, which was a different roommate than my fish roommate, we were probably bad influences on each other because we were easily persuaded to go out and do something else.
All right.
Can you share with me whether you were involved or not?
Can you share some jokes, pranks, good bull that you knew about during your student days?
You mentioned moving the senior.
That's a good one.
A lot of drown us.
And was that just dumping waste paper baskets, waste cans of water?
Yeah, water.
Yeah, taking them out to the quad and staking them out and drowning them out.
We did quite a bit of that.
Right.
On whom were the pranks played?
Why were they the targets?
Well, when I was a fish was mostly on water with the seniors.
All seniors or water the seniors?
Yeah, we had in fact, our, our CEO, as I recall, had a girlfriend in Austin that
We particularly liked getting a hold of him when his girlfriend was around and embarrassing him.
That seemed to be where most of it occurred.
Where would you, during all your A&M career, where would you all go for a good time on Saturday night?
To Huntsville.
I mean, really, we didn't spend that much time in College Station because I guess the Dixie Chicken came after I graduated.
In fact, when we were in school,
College Station was still a dry county, so we didn't do anything there.
I can remember we'd have barbecues and things like that, but generally on the weekends, we would leave.
And personally, having grown up on the Texas-Louisiana border, with the drinking age at that time being 18 in Louisiana, most of my buddies liked to

come to my house right now you said Huntsville because there were more girls over there okay all right did y'all go to a whiskey bridge and buy alcohol yes but there wasn't a lot going on I mean back you know the 67 to 71 there weren't many girls on campus and so if you wanted dates you you
had to go to Huntsville or go to Austin or go someplace else.
And probably a lot of Saturday nights were just spent with the guys hanging out and playing poker or going to a movie or going to the
Did y'all go, was it the sand pit, the rock pit?
Earlier there was a place down the Welborn Road and west a half mile or so where there was a clay pit where there had been an all-male group would go down there and drink beer and skinny dip.
That wasn't it.
Who, during all of your years, who were the memorable for you, memorable teachers, advisors, counselors that you now realize were important to you?
There were several.
One of which, I don't remember his name, but, and this is kind of an interesting story, when after my sophomore year, after two years spent in engineering,
My grades were such that they were, had been on scholastic probation.
And it was really a lack of effort on my part in terms of not attending to my grades the way I should have.
That after my sophomore year, it looked like there was a chance that I wasn't gonna be able to come back in the fall of my junior year.

And one of my classes was a civil engineering class that I had just barely made a C. I was borderline between a C and a B, but ended up getting a C. And to ensure that I would be able to come back in the fall, I needed a B.
And at the time, the instructor in that course, I believe his name was Lowry.
He was a civil engineer.
At the time, he was
either a graduate student or early on.
And I contacted him, and he said, I'll give you some extra work to do during the summer, and if you complete the work, then I'll change it right from C to B.
And I completed the work, and he did, and I was able to stay in school.
And about a year ago, I was looking at the Texas Aggie, and there was an article in there on professors that had been selected as whatever distinguished faculty members, and he was one of the
The faculty members.
That's what these watches are.
Oh, is that what that is?
Yeah.
Do you know him?
I remember him, yes.
And my wife at the time was one of the things I probably regret.
I probably still not too like to do it.
But she said you should drop him a note to tell him.
that he made a major role in you staying at A&M.
Yeah, I would endorse her because those notes are touching to the person saying, okay, I did make a difference.
Good.
28 years later, you made a huge difference.
What about some others?
Well, I had an economics professor who I would have to say was one of my favorite professors my whole four years at A&M.
His name is Bill Graham.
He was an outstanding professor.
Describe what made him outstanding.
He was a great storyteller.
He made a relatively dry subject extremely interesting and described it in a way that made complex economic principles very easy to understand.
He was always accessible, always willing to help you.
And I say that well, long before he ever became well known as Senator of the state of Texas, but he was just a top notch professor.
Another one of my favorites that made a difference was after my sophomore year, I changed to business, actually specialize in marketing.
And there was a female instructor in the marketing department named Barbara Coe, who was just an excellent
I think she's in North Texas now.
Go ahead.

And she made marketing extremely interesting, and to the extent that at the end of my sophomore year, I almost didn't make it to my junior year by the time that I was a senior, taking her courses, not because she was an easy grader, but because she finally tapped into me wanting to learn something.
I actually made the dean's list, and I attribute a lot of that to her.
To whom did you turn for academic advice during those years?
At the end of my sophomore year, I turned to Dean Hubert, mostly because I knew he was from my hometown, and he knew my parents, and frankly, I was in need of some good advice as to what to do next.
You remember, this would have been in the spring of 69, which was

not a good time not to be in school Vietnam War and he was very instrumental in helping me number one stay in school and number two being able to transfer out of engineering make believe that I didn't know him describe his manner and style of advising you as I recall as I recall he was a very courtly sort of person
very understanding, not an easy guy.
I mean, he very made me express my case very strongly as to why I needed to change why should be allowed to stay in school.
But I think was understanding of the circumstances and was wanting to help out as long as I was willing to apply myself and try to get the direction of my academic record change.
Were there, you've named a number, were there others, other faculty members and advisors?
I would think those are the ones that really come to mind the most.
All the professors in the business department were very good.
Actually, Barbara Coe's husband, I think his name was Teddy Coe, he was the accounting professor, he was very good.
There was a business professor
I believe his name was Sam Hayes.
He was also very, very good.
The business department has some outstanding professors.
What were the, in your day, what were the expected rules of classroom behavior?
What did you think was expected of you while the class was going on?
Well, I think most of them, particularly in my latter years, they very much wanted class participation.
But I don't recall it being overly structured.
I mean, I can remember taking a few catnaps in a lot of classes and no one ever running us out of class or anything.

You know, I think that back, too, in the late 60s, A&M campus, as opposed to some of the other campuses, was still a very respectful, you know, we didn't have the riots or the demonstrations or the things that other, and I think we were very respectful of our teachers.
Do you recall any kind of general sum of what it cost you to attend?
I would have to guess it was probably a couple thousand dollars a year.
And where did that money come from?
Did you earn some?
Well, I worked during the summers, every summer, and I was expected to earn my spending money, and then my parents paid for the tuition room and board, and in fact, my parents...

insisted, and they probably could have afforded a little bit more, but they insisted that I do that, and then when my son went to college here five years ago, even though I could afford it to pay even more, I paid his room and board and insisted that he earn his spending money because I thought that was a good trade-off.

let's see the MSC tell me about the the MSC and its role and what it represented to you and your fellow students it probably of any building on campus that had the most significance mainly as a meeting place we probably spent hours and hours and hours drinking coffee and smoking cigarettes and talking about everything in the world I mean that was
I have wonderful, wonderful memories of the MSC.
I mean, that was the place where everybody gathered and a lot of things took place.
Any time between classes, rather than going back to the dorm, we almost always went over to the seat.
I mean, that was the thing to do.
And I always find it interesting that other campuses don't have a central gathering place like that.
It's a very unique place.
The fact that it is a memorial, I think, made it even more special.
When I was at the Oklahoma State game a couple weeks ago, I took my wife around.
I said, now, this is part of the original MSC, and this is where we used to drink coffee, and this is what we did, and showed her where the bowling alley used to be.
Now, you are gone before the expansion.
That's what I thought.
Were you a member of any of the MSC activity groups?
I participated in...
Let's see.
Were there any famous visitors to the campus during your era that you recall?
Notable personalities.
All right, Guyon Hall.
What happened and what activities did you
Which one was that?
It was at the south end of Military Walk.
Was it torn down before you?
No, it was still there.
That was the auditorium.
But I don't remember what we did there.
I don't have any recollection of that.
Movies and chapel and lecture series and so forth.
I mean, I can remember the name, and it seems like it was called one there, but I don't know.
All right.
Let's see, were you active in any of the religious events, religious organizations?
Not active.
We went to the Newman Club.
Okay.
In fact, all four of us, because we went to Catholic high school, were somewhat involved in that.
Describe  I don't have any description of a Newman Club in that era in the file.
Describe the Newman Club.
You know, I don't think there was
I remember going to meetings, I can't even remember.
Where did y'all meet?
Over at St. Mary's?
Over across the north side?
Probably was, yeah.
That's where we went to church.
And you went to Mass there.
About how many were present?
What was a Mass like?
There was, I think, a pretty good turn.
I mean, I would say there were always, I would guess, hundreds of students that were there.
Pretty well attended.
Did you remember anything ever happening to you or that you knew of other that was at all inappropriate in relation to your being Catholic?
No, not at all.
I can honestly say I don't remember anything racial that ever happened.
You know, for me, I'd never been around a lot of Hispanics.
And that was always just
very smooth, there was not any tension.
We had, I don't recall, we didn't have a real high percentage of African Americans in the Corps, but I don't recall that there was any problems there with that.
Were there any Jewish students that you knew of?
Right now by your era the average student didn't get a nickname did they?
So years and years earlier everybody had a nickname and one of the nicknames for Jewish students was Jew boy and
but it was not a put-down, was not intended as such, and was not understood to be such.
And if you were from Amarillo, you might have been sandy, because high school was the Amarillo Golden Sandstorm.
And if you were short and wide, you might have been chunky.
but these were identifying but those were gone by your era now did did you or any of your fellow Catholic students go over for advice and counsel at the Catholic Church of the Northgate
And you didn't hear of any?
No.
All right.
Let's see.
Tell me about an Aggie football Saturday home game.
That was one of the most fun things.
What did you and your buddies do on a football weekend?
Try to get a date for one thing, which was not always easy.
A lot of my friends, if we didn't have a girlfriend at the time,
that was around there, and again, I don't want many girls there.

Probably early on, maybe the first two years I was there, mostly you brought girls from your hometown, and you had dates from, and they would drive up, in my case, drive up from Orange, or they'd drive up from Temple, or wherever they were from, and, um, we'd get together, usually they'd come in on a Friday afternoon, and, um,
